To Iccius, a student of philosophy, who was intending to join the expedition to Arabia under Aelius Gallus. The expedition, which started in 13.c. 24, was a sajlure. We learn from Epist. 1. 12. 1, written five years later, that Iccius was then managei· of some estates in Sicily (Agrippa's, if the reading is right). Nothing more is known of him.

Schema. What, Iccius, are you casting a greedy eye on the treasures of Araby and preparing to conquer the Orient? What dusky virgin, what princely boy is to become your slave? Who can deny that rivers may flow upward when you abandon philosophy for war?
